<exercises xml:id="exercises-trees" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Exercises</title>

<exercise><p> Prove that if a graph contains a closed trail then it also contains a proper cycle. </p></exercise>

<exercisegroup xml:id="exercisegroup-trees-spanning-by-inspection">
	<title>Spanning trees</title>
	<introduction><p>
		For each of the graphs in
		<xref ref="exercisegroup-trees-spanning-by-inspection" text="type-local">Exercises</xref>,
		draw a spanning tree by inspection.
	</p></introduction>
	<exercise xml:id="exercise-trees-spanning-by-inspection-1"><image xml:id="image-trees-spanning-by-inspection-1" width="17.6%">
		<description>An example graph for a spanning tree exercise.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="exercises.d/spanning-by-inspection-1.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image></exercise>
	<exercise xml:id="exercise-trees-spanning-by-inspection-2"><image xml:id="image-trees-spanning-by-inspection-2" width="30.8%">
		<description>An example graph for a spanning tree exercise.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="exercises.d/spanning-by-inspection-2.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image></exercise>
</exercisegroup>

<exercisegroup xml:id="exercisegroup-trees-spanning-by-removal">
	<title>Reducing to a spanning tree</title>
	<introduction><p>
		For each of the graphs in
		<xref ref="exercisegroup-trees-spanning-by-removal" text="type-local">Exercises</xref>,
		use the following algorithm to obtain a spanning tree.
		<ul>
			<li> If the graph contains a proper cycle, remove one edge of that cycle. </li>
			<li> If the resulting subgraph contains a proper cycle, remove one edge of that cycle. </li>
			<li> If the resulting subgraph contains a proper cycle, remove one edge of that cycle. </li>
			<li> <etc />. </li>
			<li> Continue until there are no proper cycles left. </li>
		</ul>
	</p></introduction>
	<exercise><image xml:id="image-trees-spanning-by-removal-1" width="22.9%">
		<description>An example graph for a spanning tree exercise.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="exercises.d/spanning-by-removal-1.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image></exercise>
	<exercise><image xml:id="image-trees-spanning-by-removal-2" width="65.8%">
		<description>An example graph for a spanning tree exercise.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="exercises.d/spanning-by-removal-2.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image></exercise>
</exercisegroup>

<exercisegroup xml:id="exercisegroup-trees-spanning-by-depth-breadth">
	<title>Depth-first and breadth-first spanning trees</title>
	<introduction><p>
		For each of the graphs in
		<xref ref="exercisegroup-trees-spanning-by-depth-breadth" text="type-local">Exercises</xref>,
		determine both a depth-first and breadth-first spanning tree.
		Use any vertex you like as the starting node.
	</p></introduction>
	<exercise><image xml:id="image-trees-spanning-by-depth-breadth-1" width="46.1%">
		<description>An example graph for a spanning tree exercise.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="exercises.d/spanning-by-depth-breadth-1.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image></exercise>
	<exercise><image xml:id="image-trees-spanning-by-depth-breadth-2" width="46.1%">
		<description>An example graph for a spanning tree exercise.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="exercises.d/spanning-by-depth-breadth-2.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image></exercise>
	<exercise><image xml:id="image-trees-spanning-by-depth-breadth-3" width="40.8%">
		<description>An example graph for a spanning tree exercise.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="exercises.d/spanning-by-depth-breadth-3.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image></exercise>
</exercisegroup>

</exercises>
